08445nam a22010095i 9780231534376DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315343767 a10.7312/leto111622doi  a(DE-B1597)459057  a(OCoLC)979739812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQE676b.G74 2003eb 7aSCI0540002bisacsh04a551.7/6/09722204aThe Great Rift Valleys of Pangea in Eastern North America :bVolume 1 /ced. by Peter LeTourneau, Paul Olsen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b93 line, 10 H/T  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPart I. Tectonics and Structure of Supercontinent Breakup -- t2. Introduction -- t3. Mobility of Pangea: Implications for Late Paleozoic and Early Mesozoic Paleoclimate -- t4. Progress in Understanding the Structural Geology, Basin Evolution, and Tectonic History of the Eastern North American Rift System -- t5. Tectonics of the Lantern Hill Fault, Southeastern Connecticut: Embryonic Rifting of Pangea Along the Central Atlantic Margin -- t6. Estimates of Eroded Strata Using Borehole Vitrinite Reflectance Data, Triassic Taylorsville Rift Basin, Virginia: Implications for Duration of Synrift Sedimentation and Evidence of Structural Inversion -- t7. Stress Regimes in the Newark Basin Rift: Evidence from Core and Downhole Data -- t8. A Lagerstätte of Rift-Related Tectonic Structures from the Solite Quarry, Dan River–Danville Rift Basin -- tPart II. The Central Atlantic Large Igneous Province -- t9. Introduction -- t10. Flood Basalt Provinces of the Pangean Atlantic Rift: Regional Extent and Environmental Significance -- t11. Geochemistry and Origin of Pangean and Rodinian Continental Flood Basalts -- t12. A Geographic Trend for MgO-Standardized Major Oxides in Lower Mesozoic Olivine Tholeiites of the Southeastern United States -- t13. Evidence for Predominant Lateral Magma Flow Along Major Feeder-Dike Segments of the Eastern North America Swarm Based on Magnetic Fabric -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRift basins of Triassic-Jurassic age that are associated with the breakup of the Pangean supercontinent contain an extraordinary record of the physical and biological conditions during this important period of Earth history. Rather than studying the rift basins as local features, ongoing work reveals that the Triassic-Jurassic rifts should be considered in a broader context that spans the entire proto-Atlantic realm. The rift province, collectively called the central Atlantic margin system, spans more than 45 degrees of paleolatitude and records over 35 million years of Earth history. The central Atlantic margin basins are of broad appeal to researchers interested in topics as diverse as extensional tectonics, the global magnetostratigraphic timescale, the evolution of early mammals, the appearance and diversification of dinosaurs, rift to drift crustal dynamics, astronomical forcing of climate, and models for the formation and occurrence of economic minerals and fossil fuel deposits. This extensive two-volume work offers in-depth coverage of the North American components of the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province rifts by experts in the field. In volume 1, leading researchers give thoroughly reviews and highlight recent advances in our understanding of the structural geology, tectonics, and volcanism of the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province.The companion volume, The Great Rift Valleys of Pangea in Eastern North America: Volume 2, Sedimentology, Stratigraphy, and Paleontology, 0-231-12676-X, covers such topics as sedimentary rocks, stratigraphic architecture, early dinosaur and reptile footprints, and vertebrate fossils of the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province. It is edited by Peter M. LeTourneau and Paul E. Olsen and is also available from Columbia University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGeology, StratigraphicvJurassic. 0aGeology, StratigraphicvTriassic. 0aGeology, StratigraphicyJurassic. 0aGeology, StratigraphicyTriassic. 0aRifts (Geology)zNorth America. 7aSCIENCE / Paleontology.2bisacsh1 aAckermann, Rolf V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltamura, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarton, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoer, Jelle Zeilinga de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaputi, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Richard E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Lois A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Dennis V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeTourneau, Peter M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeTourneau, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLindsey, Andrew G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLove Malinconico, MaryAnn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupo, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcHone, J. Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuttoni, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver Withjack, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlsen, Paul E., 